ce:section.ce:para:
The assay was conducted by equal amounts of solutions including: pure GQDs, dsDNA-GQDs, dsDNA-GQDs+ 40U/ml HpaII, dsDNA-GQDs+ 10U/ml M.SssI, dsDNA-GQDs+ different concentration of M.SssI and 40U/mlM.SssI at the same condition. Then the Fluorescence anisotropy (FA) of them was measured. The pure GQDs were regarded as the control and its FA was 0.231. Conjugation with DNA made the FA of GQDs increase from 0.206 to 0.298. By using different concentrations of M.SssI methyltransferase and HpaII changing in FAs was observed. Different amounts of M.SssI were incubated with equal amount of dsDNA-GQDs then 40U/ml HpaII was added, after adequate reaction FAs or Δr of all were measured. As it is shown in Fig. 4
                         the FAs of pure GQDs and dsDNA-GQDs+40U/ml HpaII were the lowest. To evaluate the sensitivity of this method various concentrations of M.SssI were tested. The FAs were increased with increase of M.SssI concentration and there was a linear correlation between Δr and M.SssI concentrations. Therefore, it was confirmed that the probe constructed by dsDNA-GQDs can be used to characterize methyltransferase activity with monitoring the interaction between DNA and GQDs based on change in FAs. In presence of M.SssI more conjugated DNAs were methylated that HpaII could not cleave them so the mass or volume of GQDs increased and lead to an increase in FA (Fig. 5
                        ).
